```yaml
review:
  document: <document identifier or path>
  reviewer: vmodel-skill-review-architecture
  date: <YYYY-MM-DD>

  verdict: <APPROVED | REJECTED | DESIGN_ISSUE>
  # Decision-table outcome — see SKILL.md "Verdict decision table".
  # Precedence: DESIGN_ISSUE wins over REJECTED. The meta-gate routes per
  # upstream-traceability: if `check.spec-ambiguity-test.fail` fires AND the
  # failure is upstream-traceable (parent Requirements ambiguous, governing
  # ADR missing the load-bearing decision), verdict is DESIGN_ISSUE; if the
  # failure is internal to the artifact, verdict is REJECTED.

  inputs_provided:
    architecture_document: true
    parent_requirements: <true | false>
    governing_adrs: <true | false | partial>
  # When parent_requirements is false, traceability checks cannot be run —
  # halt with `missing-inputs` rather than approving blind.
  # When governing_adrs is false-or-partial AND `governing_adrs:` in the
  # front-matter is non-empty AND specific entries do not resolve, halt
  # with `missing-inputs`.

  perspectives_applied:
    - architect          # decomposition, interfaces, composition correctness
    - integrator         # cross-component flow, sequence-diagram coverage, wiring
    - operator           # deployment intent, resilience, observability, security

  findings:
    # Zero or more findings, one per failed check.
    # Each follows finding.yaml.tmpl.
    - id: F-001
      element_id: <decomposition-id | interface-name | "GLOBAL">
      check_failed: <dotted catalog identifier>
      severity: <hard_reject | soft_reject | info>
      category: <decomposition | interface | composition | quality-attribute | resilience | security | observability | rationale | adr | traceability | retrofit | meta-gate>
      evidence: |
        <verbatim quote or location reference from the artifact under review>
      recommended_action: |
        <generic pointer; never specific replacement wording>

    # ... more findings ...

  summary: |
    # 2-4 sentences. Cite the dominant findings, not every finding.
    # Verdict justification: which trigger fired, why DESIGN_ISSUE vs REJECTED if
    # applicable, whether all inputs were provided.
    # When DESIGN_ISSUE: name the upstream artifact (Requirements / ADR) that needs
    # to revise before this Architecture can reach APPROVED.
    # When REJECTED for a hard-reject: name the refusal class (A/B/C/broken-reference).

  recommended_next_action: |
    # APPROVED  → "Proceed to Detailed Design (per leaf) and TestSpec authoring."
    # REJECTED  → "Hand findings to the matched author skill for rewrite."
    # DESIGN_ISSUE → "Escalate to <upstream artifact name>; rewriting this
    #                Architecture in place will not resolve the upstream gap."

  counts:
    hard_reject: <integer>
    soft_reject: <integer>
    info: <integer>
    design_issue: <integer>      # count of meta-gate findings; usually 0 or 1
```

## Notes for emitting the verdict

- `verdict` matches the decision table in SKILL.md exactly. Do not override.
- If the document is APPROVED but the review surfaced `info` findings, list them — they are useful observations even though they do not affect the verdict.
- The `summary` field should be the first thing a human reader sees. Aim for: *"Verdict: \<X>. Trigger: \<dominant cause>. Inputs: \<provided / partial / missing — implications>."*
- For DESIGN_ISSUE verdicts, name the upstream artifact in `summary` and `recommended_next_action`. Do not name the matched author skill explicitly — say "the matched author skill" (locked convention §2.4 sister-naming).
- For REJECTED verdicts triggered by a hard-reject finding, the `summary` names the refusal class (A — retrofit honesty / B — DD-vs-Architecture boundary / C — composition / broken-reference) so the consumer of the verdict knows the shape of the rewrite.
